{
  "In microeconomics, the equilibrium price occurs where:": "",
  "Supply is zero": "",
  "Demand is zero": "",
  "The government sets the price": "",
  "Supply equals demand": "",
  "Equilibrium is where supply meets demand, determining both the market price and quantity. This concept also applies to stock prices, which settle where buyers and sellers agree.": "",
  "A firm maximizes profit at the output level where:": "",
  "Revenue is highest regardless of cost": "",
  "Total cost is minimized": "",
  "It produces the maximum possible quantity": "",
  "Marginal cost equals marginal revenue (MC = MR)": "",
  "MC = MR is the profit-maximizing rule. Producing beyond this point means the cost of the next unit exceeds the revenue it generates, reducing total profit.": "",
  "If a 10% price increase causes only a 3% drop in quantity demanded, the product has:": "",
  "Elastic demand": "",
  "Perfectly elastic demand": "",
  "Unitary elastic demand": "",
  "Inelastic demand": "",
  "When the percentage change in quantity (3%) is less than the percentage change in price (10%), demand is inelastic. The company has pricing power because revenue increases with price hikes.": "",
  "Companies with inelastic demand can raise prices because consumers:": "",
  "Are legally required to buy, which is a common assumption in the field": "",
  "Have unlimited budgets, since the prevailing theory about companies would support this particular": "",
  "Receive government subsidies to buy regardless of prevailing conditions in practice": "",
  "Do not significantly reduce purchases — typically because the product is a necessity, has few substitutes, or is unique": "",
  "Inelastic demand means consumers keep buying even at higher prices. Examples include essential medications, gasoline, and utility services. This translates to pricing power for investors evaluating companies.": "",
  "GDP growth of 3% typically corresponds to stock market returns that are:": "",
  "Positive, because economic growth drives corporate earnings growth": "",
  "Negative within the broader context of growth analysis": "",
  "Zero, even when conditions shift significantly": "",
  "Exactly 3%, especially during periods of significant change": "",
  "Economic growth creates more consumer spending, higher corporate revenue, and increased profits — all of which tend to drive stock prices higher, though not in a 1:1 relationship.": "",
  "When unemployment rises significantly, the typical cascade effect on markets is:": "",
  "Higher stock prices due to lower labor costs": "",
  "Increased consumer confidence": "",
  "Less income leads to less spending, which leads to lower corporate revenue and lower stock prices": "",
  "No impact on financial markets": "",
  "Rising unemployment triggers a negative cascade: less income, less consumer spending, lower corporate revenue, lower profits, and ultimately lower stock prices. Understanding this chain helps investors anticipate market movements.": "",
  "The Phillips Curve historically shows an inverse relationship between:": "",
  "Imports and exports": "",
  "GDP and interest rates": "",
  "Inflation and unemployment": "",
  "Stocks and bonds": "",
  "The Phillips Curve suggests that lower unemployment tends to coincide with higher inflation, and vice versa. This tradeoff is central to Federal Reserve monetary policy decisions.": "",
  "Quantitative easing (QE) occurs when the Federal Reserve:": "",
  "Sells all of its bond holdings": "",
  "Buys bonds to inject money into the economy and lower long-term interest rates": "",
  "Raises interest rates aggressively": "",
  "Prints physical currency for distribution": "",
  "QE is an unconventional monetary policy tool where the Fed purchases government and mortgage-backed bonds, increasing money supply and pushing down long-term interest rates to stimulate borrowing and investment.": "",
  "QE generally leads to _____ asset prices.": "",
  "Lower": "",
  "Unpredictably volatile": "",
  "Higher": "",
  "Unchanged": "",
  "QE pushes investors toward riskier assets (stocks, real estate) because low bond yields make them less attractive. The abundant liquidity also inflates asset prices across the board.": "",
  "Persistent trade deficits tend to put _____ pressure on the domestic currency.": "",
  "Downward": "",
  "Only temporary": "",
  "No": "",
  "Upward": "",
  "When a country imports more than it exports, more domestic currency flows out to pay for imports, creating selling pressure that tends to weaken the currency over time.": "",
  "What is comparative advantage?": "",
  "Selling products at lower prices regardless of cost": "",
  "The ability to produce a good at a lower opportunity cost than another producer, creating mutual benefits from trade": "",
  "The ability to produce everything more cheaply than other countries": "",
  "Having more natural resources than competitors": "",
  "Comparative advantage means producing a good at a lower opportunity cost. Even if one country is better at producing everything, both countries benefit by specializing and trading — the basis for international trade theory.": "",
  "What characterizes a monopoly market structure?": "",
  "A single seller with no close substitutes, allowing above-normal profits due to barriers to entry": "",
  "Government ownership of all production": "",
  "Two large firms that always cooperate on pricing": "",
  "Many firms with identical products and zero economic profit in the long run": "",
  "A monopoly has a single seller, high barriers to entry, and no close substitutes. This allows persistent above-normal profits — relevant for investors evaluating a company's competitive moat and pricing power.": "",
  "What is consumer surplus?": "",
  "The difference between what consumers are willing to pay and what they actually pay": "",
  "Government tax revenue from sales": "",
  "The excess supply of goods in the market": "",
  "The profit earned by producers": "",
  "Consumer surplus is the benefit consumers receive when they pay less than their maximum willingness to pay. In financial markets, this concept applies to buying assets below their perceived intrinsic value.": "",
  "What is information asymmetry in markets?": "",
  "When the government withholds economic data": "",
  "When all market participants have equal information": "",
  "When prices are publicly available to everyone": "",
  "When one party in a transaction has more or better information than the other, leading to adverse selection or moral hazard": "",
  "Information asymmetry causes market failures. Examples include insider trading (stock markets), the 'lemons problem' (used cars), and moral hazard (insurance). This drives the need for financial regulation and disclosure requirements.": "",
  "What is game theory as applied to business?": "",
  "A theory about recreational gaming profits, especially during periods of significant change": "",
  "A technique for minimizing taxes according to widely held views on this topic": "",
  "A framework for analyzing strategic decisions where outcomes depend on the actions of multiple decision-makers": "",
  "A method for predicting stock prices according to widely held views on this topic": "",
  "Game theory analyzes strategic interactions where each party's best decision depends on what others do. Applications include competitive pricing, market entry decisions, and advertising strategies.": "",
  "What is the tragedy of the commons?": "",
  "When individuals acting in their own self-interest deplete or destroy a shared resource, harming the collective": "",
  "When common stocks lose value in a market crash": "",
  "When public parks become overcrowded": "",
  "When the government takes private property": "",
  "The tragedy of the commons occurs when shared resources are overused because individuals prioritize personal gain. In finance, examples include excessive risk-taking that threatens market stability (as in the 2008 crisis).": "",
  "What does behavioral economics reveal about financial decision-making?": "",
  "People always make perfectly rational financial decisions": "",
  "People systematically deviate from rational behavior due to cognitive biases, affecting financial outcomes": "",
  "Only math skills determine financial success": "",
  "Emotions have no impact on investment decisions": "",
  "Behavioral economics shows that biases like loss aversion, overconfidence, herd mentality, and anchoring cause people to make predictably irrational financial decisions. Awareness of these biases improves outcomes.": "",
  "What does the AD-AS (Aggregate Demand-Aggregate Supply) model show?": "",
  "Only international trade flows under most circumstances involving Aggregate": "",
  "Only the labor market without accounting for additional influences": "",
  "The overall price level and total output of an economy, and how shifts affect inflation and GDP": "",
  "Individual product prices in a single market under most circumstances involving": "",
  "The AD-AS model is the macroeconomic framework showing how aggregate demand and supply determine the overall price level and real GDP. Shifts in either curve affect inflation, growth, and financial markets broadly.": "",
  "What is fiscal policy?": "",
  "Government decisions about taxation and spending to influence the economy": "",
  "International trade agreements": "",
  "Corporate dividend policy": "",
  "The Federal Reserve's control of interest rates": "",
  "Fiscal policy involves government taxation and spending decisions. Expansionary fiscal policy (increased spending or tax cuts) stimulates growth; contractionary policy (reduced spending or tax increases) slows it.": "",
  "What is monetary policy?": "",
  "Government decisions about tax rates": "",
  "The Federal Reserve's management of money supply and interest rates to influence economic conditions": "",
  "Corporate decisions about capital structure": "",
  "Congressional decisions about the federal budget": "",
  "Monetary policy is conducted by the Federal Reserve through tools like the federal funds rate, reserve requirements, and open market operations (including QE). It directly impacts borrowing costs, investment returns, and asset prices.": "",
  "A pharmaceutical company raises the price of a critical medication by 15%, and quantity demanded falls by only 2%. What is the price elasticity of demand, and what does this mean for revenue?": "",
  "Elasticity = 7.5; revenue decreases significantly": "",
  "Elasticity = 0.13; revenue increases because demand is highly inelastic": "",
  "Elasticity = 1.0; revenue stays the same": "",
  "Elasticity = 0.13; revenue decreases": "",
  "Price elasticity = % change in quantity / % change in price = 2% / 15% = 0.13. Since elasticity < 1 (inelastic), the price increase raises total revenue because the quantity drop is minimal. This is typical for essential medications.": "",
  "The unemployment rate drops from 6% to 3.5%. Based on the Phillips Curve relationship, what would you expect to happen to inflation?": "",
  "Inflation would likely decrease": "",
  "Inflation would become negative (deflation)": "",
  "Inflation would likely increase as tight labor markets push wages and prices higher": "",
  "Inflation would remain exactly the same": "",
  "The Phillips Curve predicts an inverse relationship: as unemployment falls, competition for workers drives wages up, increasing production costs and consumer prices. The Fed monitors this tradeoff when setting interest rates.": "",
  "The Federal Reserve announces a new round of quantitative easing, purchasing $100 billion in bonds monthly. As a financial advisor, how would you expect this to affect your clients' stock and bond portfolios?": "",
  "Only bond prices would change; stocks would be unaffected": "",
  "Both would remain unchanged since QE only affects banks": "",
  "Both stocks and bonds would likely decline": "",
  "Stocks would likely rise (more liquidity, lower rates push investors to riskier assets) and bond prices would rise (Fed buying pushes bond prices up)": "",
  "QE typically lifts both stocks (excess liquidity seeks returns in equities) and bonds (Fed purchases drive bond prices up and yields down). This is why QE periods historically coincide with strong market performance.": "",
  "Country X has a persistent trade deficit of $50 billion/year with Country Y. Over time, what would you expect to happen to Country X's currency relative to Country Y's?": "",
  "Both currencies would weaken equally": "",
  "Country X's currency would strengthen": "",
  "Country X's currency would weaken as more of it flows out to pay for imports": "",
  "Neither currency would be affected": "",
  "A persistent trade deficit means Country X is buying more from Y than it sells. This creates excess supply of Country X's currency in foreign exchange markets, putting downward pressure on its value.": "",
  "Country A can produce 100 cars or 500 computers per day. Country B can produce 50 cars or 400 computers per day. Which country has the comparative advantage in car production?": "",
  "Country A — opportunity cost of 1 car is 5 computers vs. Country B's 8 computers": "",
  "Country B — it produces fewer cars, so each one is more valuable": "",
  "Country B — it has lower total production costs": "",
  "Neither has a comparative advantage": "",
  "Country A's opportunity cost per car = 500/100 = 5 computers. Country B's opportunity cost per car = 400/50 = 8 computers. Country A gives up fewer computers per car, so it has the comparative advantage in cars.": "",
  "In a competitive market, a widget sells for $10 with zero economic profit. A monopolist produces the same widget at the same cost but charges $16. Consumer surplus in the monopoly scenario has:": "",
  "Remained the same since the product is identical": "",
  "Decreased because consumers pay a higher price and buy fewer units, creating deadweight loss": "",
  "Increased because consumers get a premium product": "",
  "Become negative": "",
  "Monopolies reduce consumer surplus by charging higher prices and producing less output. The difference between competitive and monopoly outcomes creates deadweight loss — value that neither consumers nor the producer captures.": "",
  "A government increases spending by $200 billion financed by borrowing during a recession. According to crowding-out theory, what is the likely effect on private investment?": "",
  "Government borrowing pushes interest rates higher, which may reduce private investment spending": "",
  "Interest rates drop, boosting private investment": "",
  "Private investment increases proportionally": "",
  "Private investment is completely unaffected": "",
  "Crowding out occurs when government borrowing competes with private borrowers for limited loanable funds, pushing interest rates higher and potentially reducing private business investment and consumer borrowing.": "",
  "Two competing airlines are deciding whether to lower fares. If both lower fares, each earns $5M. If neither lowers, each earns $8M. If one lowers and the other does not, the lower-fare airline earns $10M while the other earns $2M. This is an example of:": "",
  "A prisoner's dilemma — both airlines have an incentive to cut fares even though mutual cooperation yields a better collective outcome": "",
  "A natural monopoly because conventional analysis of earns suggests this would be the expected result": "",
  "Comparative advantage given that prevailing earns conditions tend to reinforce this particular trajectory": "",
  "Perfect competition, since standard models of earns behavior predict this outcome under normal conditions": "",
  "This is a classic prisoner's dilemma. Each airline's dominant strategy is to lower fares (earning $10M or $5M vs. $8M or $2M), but the Nash equilibrium ($5M each) is worse than if both cooperated ($8M each).": "",
  "An oil supply shock reduces aggregate supply (AS shifts left). According to the AD-AS model, what happens to the overall price level and real GDP?": "",
  "Prices rise and GDP falls — a condition known as stagflation": "",
  "Both prices and GDP rise together": "",
  "Prices fall and GDP rises": "",
  "Neither prices nor GDP change": "",
  "A leftward shift of AS means higher production costs. This causes the price level to rise (inflation) while real GDP falls (recession) — the painful combination known as stagflation, as seen during the 1970s oil crises.": "",
  "The CPI was 280 last year and 290 this year. A bond yields 5% and the stock market returned 8%. What is the approximate inflation rate, and what are the real returns on each investment?": "",
  "Inflation ~1%; real bond return ~4%, real stock return ~7%": "",
  "Inflation ~3.6%; real bond return ~5%, real stock return ~8%": "",
  "Inflation ~3.6%; real bond return ~1.4%, real stock return ~4.4%": "",
  "Inflation ~10%; real bond return -5%, real stock return -2%": "",
  "Inflation = (290 - 280) / 280 = 3.57% ≈ 3.6%. Real return ≈ nominal - inflation. Real bond return = 5% - 3.6% = 1.4%. Real stock return = 8% - 3.6% = 4.4%. Inflation significantly erodes purchasing power of returns.": ""
